Malaik, let’s treat this the way it actually comes up in interviews. Interviewers don’t want textbook definitions. They want to know how it fits into a real microservice system like the one you described.

You already have the right mental model:
multiple services, different DBs, some async processing, modules talking to each other.

Now let’s connect API Gateway + Reverse Proxy to that world.


---

1. First understand the problem they solve

Imagine your system has these services:

User Service
Order Service
Payment Service
Metadata Service
Notification Service

Each service runs independently.

Example URLs:

http://user-service:8081
http://order-service:8082
http://payment-service:8083

Now imagine a frontend calling them.

Without any gateway:

Frontend → user-service
Frontend → order-service
Frontend → payment-service
Frontend → metadata-service

Problems appear quickly:

• frontend needs to know all service URLs
• security must be added to every service
• rate limiting everywhere
• logging everywhere
• versioning becomes messy

So companies add one entry point.

Client
  ↓
API Gateway
  ↓
Microservices

That’s the main idea.


---

2. What is an API Gateway

Simple definition:

API Gateway is the single entry point for all client requests in a microservice system.

It sits in front of services and routes requests.

Client
   ↓
API Gateway
   ↓
User Service
Order Service
Payment Service

Example request:

GET /users/123

Gateway routes it to:

user-service

Another request:

POST /orders

Gateway routes it to:

order-service


---

3. What an API Gateway actually does

This is what interviewers expect.

1 Routing

/users → user-service
/orders → order-service
/payments → payment-service


---

2 Authentication

Instead of every service validating tokens:

Gateway validates JWT
↓
Forward request to service

Services trust the gateway.


---

3 Rate limiting

Example:

max 100 requests per second per user

Gateway blocks excess traffic.


---

4 Request aggregation

Example:

Frontend needs:

user profile
orders
payments

Instead of 3 calls:

frontend → gateway
gateway → user service
gateway → order service
gateway → payment service

Gateway combines response.


---

5 Logging & monitoring

Centralized place for:

request logs
metrics
tracing


---

4. Real tools used as API Gateway

In Spring ecosystem:

• Spring Cloud Gateway
• Netflix Zuul (older)

Industry tools:

• AWS API Gateway
• Kong
• NGINX
• Traefik


---

5. Now what is a Reverse Proxy

This is where many developers get confused.

A reverse proxy is a server that sits in front of backend servers and forwards client requests to them.

Example:

Client
   ↓
NGINX (reverse proxy)
   ↓
Backend servers

Example routing:

/api → backend1
/images → backend2
/videos → backend3

Clients never talk directly to backend servers.

They only talk to the proxy.


---

6. Difference between Forward Proxy vs Reverse Proxy

Just so you're clear.

Forward proxy:

Client → Proxy → Internet

Example:

Corporate internet proxy.


---

Reverse proxy:

Client → Proxy → Backend Servers

Example:

NGINX in front of microservices.


---

7. Relationship between API Gateway and Reverse Proxy

Here’s the key insight.

API Gateway is basically a specialized reverse proxy for APIs.

Reverse proxy features:

• routing
• load balancing
• SSL termination

API gateway adds:

• authentication
• rate limiting
• API management
• request transformation
• analytics

So:

Reverse Proxy  → traffic router
API Gateway    → smart router for APIs


---

8. Example architecture (similar to what you described)

Let’s say your metadata system works like this.

Client
   ↓
API Gateway
   ↓
Ingestion Service
   ↓
SQS
   ↓
Processing Service A
   ↓
Database
   ↓
Processing Service B

Gateway handles:

POST /metadata

Routes to:

metadata-ingestion-service

Then ingestion service pushes message to:

SQS

Then:

processor A
processor B

Work asynchronously.


---

9. How to answer in an interview (simple)

If interviewer asks:

What is API Gateway?

Answer:

> API Gateway acts as a single entry point for all client requests in a microservices architecture. Instead of clients calling multiple services directly, they call the gateway. The gateway handles routing, authentication, rate limiting, and monitoring before forwarding requests to the appropriate microservice.




---

If they ask:

What is reverse proxy?

Answer:

> A reverse proxy sits in front of backend servers and forwards client requests to them. Clients never communicate directly with backend services. It helps with load balancing, security, and hiding internal service architecture.




---

10. If they ask difference

You say:

> A reverse proxy mainly handles traffic routing and load balancing. An API Gateway is built on top of the reverse proxy concept but adds API-specific features like authentication, rate limiting, request transformation, and API monitoring.




---

11. One senior-level insight (interview gold)

Many real systems use both.

Example:

Client
  ↓
Cloudflare
  ↓
NGINX (reverse proxy)
  ↓
API Gateway
  ↓
Microservices

Each layer adds control.


---

12. One question interviewers LOVE to ask

Why not call microservices directly?

Answer:

• security centralized
• clients don’t need service discovery
• easier API versioning
• rate limiting
• monitoring


